4 Urgency Asterisks
*******************

The priority cookie may carry one or more trailing ‘*’ characters inside
the brackets, immediately after the integer rank, to mark extra urgency.
This follows the traditional paper-list convention of flagging an item
with one or more stars.

     ** TODO [A1]    standard
     ** TODO [A1*]   urgent
     ** TODO [A1**]  very urgent
     ** TODO [A1***] most urgent

   Asterisks inside the brackets are safe because Org's headline
detection matches ‘^\*+ ’ anchored to the start of a line.  The ‘*’
characters that appear between ‘[’ and ‘]’ mid-line are plain text from
Org's point of view.

   ‘oltp-sort-region’ weighs asterisks within each priority group as
follows.

  1. A letter difference always dominates the asterisk count.  Plain
     ‘[A1]’ still outranks ‘[B1***]’.

  2. Within the same letter, more asterisks outranks fewer asterisks.
     ‘[A1***]’ outranks ‘[A1**]’ which outranks ‘[A1*]’.

  3. Any asterisk-bearing cookie outranks a same-letter cookie without
     asterisks.  ‘[A99*]’ outranks ‘[A1]’.

  4. Within the same letter and asterisk count, ties break on the
     integer rank, smaller first.  ‘[A1*]’ outranks ‘[A2*]’.

‘oltp-prioritize-region’ preserves any asterisks that are already inside
a cookie, so they survive renumbering.  The command never invents
asterisks; they remain a manual urgency marker that you type into the
cookie yourself.

   ‘oltp-strip-region’ removes the entire bracketed cookie, so asterisks
come out with it; the ‘TODO’ keyword stays.


