5 Commands
**********

 -- Command: oltp-prioritize-region beg end
     Add ‘TODO [XY]’ cookies to every ‘**+’ headline between BEG and
     END.  Blank lines start a new priority group, so the first
     contiguous block of headlines becomes ‘A1’, ‘A2’, ‘A3’, the next
     block becomes ‘B1’, ‘B2’, and so on.  Headlines that already carry
     ‘TODO’ or a ‘[XY]’ cookie are normalized in place, so the command
     is idempotent.  Non-headline content lines between headlines (for
     example ‘SCHEDULED’ lines, drawers, body text) do not break a group
     and do not consume a priority slot.  Trailing urgency asterisks
     inside an existing cookie are preserved across the renumbering; see
     *note Urgency Asterisks::.

 -- Command: oltp-strip-region beg end
     Remove ‘[XY]’ cookies from every Org headline in the region.  The
     ‘TODO’ keyword is preserved.  Trailing asterisks inside the cookie
     are part of the cookie and come out with it.

 -- Command: oltp-sort-region beg end
     Sort ‘**+’ subtrees in the region by ‘[XY]’ priority.  Each
     subtree, from its ‘**+’ line up to (but not including) the next ‘*’
     or ‘**+’ headline, moves as a unit so ‘SCHEDULED’ lines and body
     text follow their headline.  Level-1 ‘*’ headlines act as section
     boundaries and stay in place, so sorting across the whole
     ‘tasks.org’ file re-orders items inside each ‘* Do it ...’ section
     independently.  Within a letter, more asterisks outranks fewer and
     any asterisk-bearing cookie outranks a plain one; see *note Urgency
     Asterisks::.  Subtrees without a cookie sort to the end of their
     section in original relative order.

 -- Command: oltp-add-project-tag
     Append an Org tag to the current headline.  The project name is
     read from the SQLite database referenced by ‘oltp-db-path’ through
     ‘completing-read’, sanitized into an Org-compatible tag, and
     applied through ‘org-set-tags’ so existing tags and alignment are
     preserved.  Signals an error when point is not on a headline.

 -- Command: oltp-tag-region beg end
     Walk the region and prompt for a project tag once per ‘**+’
     headline.  Non-headline lines are skipped.

 -- Command: oltp-init-tasks-file &optional force
     Create the ‘tasks.org’ file at ‘oltp-tasks-file’, pre-populated
     with the eleven top-level headlines from
     ‘oltp-tasks-file-headlines’.  With prefix argument FORCE, an
     existing file is overwritten.  Without FORCE, an existing file
     signals an error.

 -- Command: oltp-schedule-tasks-file
     Walk ‘oltp-tasks-file’ and add (or replace) a ‘SCHEDULED:’ line
     under each ‘** TODO’ based on the parent ‘*’ section.  Sections
     that have no entry in ‘oltp-section-date-functions’ are skipped
     silently.  Safe to re-run; existing ‘SCHEDULED’ lines are replaced
     rather than duplicated.

 -- Command: oltp-prioritize-and-schedule-tasks-file
     Convenience command equivalent to ‘oltp-schedule-tasks-file’.
     Prioritization remains a manual, region-based operation because
     priority groups follow blank-line breaks rather than the parent
     section.


