6 Customization
***************

 -- User Option: oltp-tasks-file
     Absolute path to the tasks file managed by this package.  Both the
     directory and the file name are part of this option, so you can
     keep ‘tasks.org’ wherever you like.

     Default: ‘~/tasks.org’.

 -- User Option: oltp-tasks-file-headlines
     Top-level headlines written by ‘oltp-init-tasks-file’.  The order
     is significant.  Each entry should have a corresponding entry in
     ‘oltp-section-date-functions’ so that ‘oltp-schedule-tasks-file’
     can pick a ‘SCHEDULED’ date for the TODOs under it.

     Default: a list of eleven names ranging from ‘"Do it today"’ to
     ‘"Do it next year"’.

 -- User Option: oltp-org-todo-keyword
     Org keyword used in front of the priority cookie.

     Default: ‘"TODO"’.

 -- User Option: oltp-db-path
     Absolute path to the SQLite database that holds project metadata.

     Default: ‘~/60003TimeTracking/cb/tenKprojects.db’.

 -- User Option: oltp-db-table
     Table inside ‘oltp-db-path’ that holds the project rows.  When
     ‘nil’, the package walks every table in the database and picks the
     first one whose schema includes a column named by ‘oltp-db-column’.

     Default: ‘nil’ (auto-detect).

 -- User Option: oltp-db-column
     Column name to read project names from.

     Default: ‘"ProjectDirectory"’.

 -- User Option: oltp-tag-use-basename
     When non-‘nil’, the Org tag is built from the basename of the
     project path returned by the database.  When ‘nil’, the full path
     is sanitized into a tag.

     Default: ‘t’.

 -- User Option: oltp-section-date-functions
     Alist mapping a section headline name to a zero-argument function
     returning an Emacs time value.  ‘oltp-schedule-tasks-file’ uses the
     returned time as the ‘SCHEDULED’ date for every TODO under the
     matching section.

     Default entries map each of the eleven standard headlines to a
     reasonable target date.  See *note Section Dates::.


